<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="568" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1359,2032]" pageId="7" pageNumber="568">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,420,1503,1528]" pageId="7" pageNumber="568">Description. Male.</emphasis>
Frontal rostrum with obvious transverse margin, 2.5-3 times as wide as 1st antennal joint. Pronotum saddle shaped, disc narrower in front, and widened with the posterior margin arc, lateral carinae with a little convex part in the middle, tympanum on both sides of fore tibiae with same size, legs long and spination, fore femora with 2-3 interior ventral spines, fore tibiae with four lines of spines, few pairs of spines on two lines of dorsal margin, but 6-7 pairs of spines on two lines of ventral margin, no spines on middle femora, middle tibiae with four lines of spines, few pairs of spines on two lines of dorsal margin, but 6-7 pairs of spines on two lines of ventral margin, hind femora with 4-6 interior ventral spines, hind tibiae with four lines of spines, many pairs of spines on two lines of dorsal margin, but only apical half margin with spines in hind tibiae. Forewing long with obvious mirror, hindwing little longer than forewing. The length of abdomen no longer than half of forewing (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1878,1900]" captionTargetBox="[304,1286,491,1845]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[304,1286,491,1845]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Mecopoda spp. from China. A-C: M. elongata elongata, DE: M. fallax sp. nov., FG: M. niponensis, HI: M. hainanensis sp. nov., J: M. mamorata sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2640102/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="568">Fig. 2H</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[199,289,1827,1852]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1987,2009]" captionTargetBox="[188,1393,193,1964]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[188,1393,193,1964]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. M. hainanensis in living condition. A: male, B: female." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2640110/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="568">Fig. 7A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1359,2032]" pageId="7" pageNumber="568">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,293,1863,1888]" pageId="7" pageNumber="568">Female.</emphasis>
Similar to male, ovipositor long (only shorter than 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Liu &amp; Shen &amp; Gong &amp; Zhang &amp; He" authorityYear="2019" box="[885,1039,1864,1887]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Mecopoda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="568" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mamorata">
<emphasis box="[885,908,1864,1887]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="568">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[924,1039,1864,1887]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="568">mamorata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and straight with apical part little upwards curved (
<figureCitation box="[344,422,1899,1924]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1878,1900]" captionTargetBox="[304,1286,491,1845]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[304,1286,491,1845]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Mecopoda spp. from China. A-C: M. elongata elongata, DE: M. fallax sp. nov., FG: M. niponensis, HI: M. hainanensis sp. nov., J: M. mamorata sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2640102/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="568">
Fig. 
<date box="[397,422,1900,1924]" pageId="7" pageNumber="568">2I</date>
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[434,522,1899,1924]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1987,2009]" captionTargetBox="[188,1393,193,1964]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[188,1393,193,1964]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. M. hainanensis in living condition. A: male, B: female." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2640110/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="568">Fig. 7B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1359,2032]" pageId="7" pageNumber="568">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1935,1960]" pageId="7" pageNumber="568">Coloration.</emphasis>
Nearly brown. Fore femora black and fore tibiae yellow. We checked all 
<typeStatus box="[1209,1257,1936,1960]" pageId="7" pageNumber="568">type</typeStatus>
specimens and found this colour contrast were very stable. 0-4 vague white spots on forewing. 3 small black spots on forewing in one individual.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
