</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="569" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1521,1906]" pageId="8" pageNumber="569">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,482,1557,1582]" pageId="8" pageNumber="569">Measurements (in mm).</emphasis>
Male: SZ 56.09-60.46, PR 7.92-10.62, FW 47.54-50.76, HW 49.16-52.95, HF 38.42- 40.14; Female: SZ 61.29-63.40, PR 8.32-8.74, FW 51.76-55.95, HW 55.04-57.02, HF 45.50-48.80, OV 30.11- 33.09.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="569" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1521,1906]" box="[199,540,1665,1690]" pageId="8" pageNumber="569">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1665,1690]" pageId="8" pageNumber="569">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[359,426,1665,1690]" name="China" pageId="8" pageNumber="569">China</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[441,528,1665,1690]" country="China" name="Hainan" pageId="8" pageNumber="569">Hainan</collectingRegion>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1521,1906]" pageId="8" pageNumber="569">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,265,1701,1726]" pageId="8" pageNumber="569">Song.</emphasis>
The first part of this species is very long, sometimes it lasts one hour in wild. The first part contains 0.66± 
<geoCoordinate box="[216,275,1737,1762]" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="8" pageNumber="569" precision="555" value="-0.03">0.03s</geoCoordinate>
duration and 0.88± 
<geoCoordinate box="[503,562,1738,1762]" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="8" pageNumber="569" precision="555" value="-0.08">0.08s</geoCoordinate>
interval. The second part is continuous with 0.136± 
<geoCoordinate box="[1169,1241,1737,1762]" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="8" pageNumber="569" precision="55" value="-0.001">0.001s</geoCoordinate>
cycle repeatedly (
<figureCitation box="[159,249,1773,1798]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1053,1075]" captionTargetBox="[161,1410,190,1019]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,175,1031]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Calling songs of Mecopoda spp. from China. A: M. elongata elongata, B: M. niponensis, C: M. fallax sp. nov., D: M. hainanensis sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2640108/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="569">Fig. 5D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="569" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1521,1906]" pageId="8" pageNumber="569">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,262,1809,1834]" pageId="8" pageNumber="569">Note.</emphasis>
It is an endemic species in Hainan Island (
<figureCitation box="[740,808,1809,1834]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1454,1476]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[284,1291,213,1425]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 6. Distribution of Mecopoda spp." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3351353/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="569">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). However, 
<taxonomicName authority="elongata" authorityName="elongata (Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[944,1184,1809,1834]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Mecopoda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="569" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="elongata" subSpecies="elongata">
<emphasis box="[944,967,1810,1833]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="569">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[981,1184,1809,1834]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="569">elongata elongata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Haan" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[1238,1395,1810,1833]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Mecopoda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="569" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="niponensis">
<emphasis box="[1238,1261,1810,1833]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="569">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1275,1395,1810,1833]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="569">niponensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are also distributed in Hainan. We suspect that these two species are spread by human activity, because we only collected them near farm, but never in natural reserve.
</paragraph>
